00:03:14.070 --> 00:03:18.160
with a relatively broad
question for someone

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:20.420
who I think thinks a lot
about issues globally.

00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:22.800
Oisika, could you
just talk a little bit

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:25.690
about what do we mean
by gender equality,

00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:31.330
and when we think about where
we are today in the world what

00:03:31.330 --> 00:03:34.010
progress still needs to be
made, and why are we talking

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:35.757
about this issue still today?

00:03:35.757 --> 00:03:37.840
OISIKA CHAKRABARTI: Sure,
that's a great question.

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:40.020
And firstly, thank you
for hosting this panel.

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:42.490
This is a great
conversation to have,

00:03:42.490 --> 00:03:45.530
and of course a topic very,
very close to my heart

00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:48.220
and all our hearts, I guess.

00:03:48.220 --> 00:03:50.230
So what do we mean
by gender equality?

00:03:50.230 --> 00:03:53.290
We mean a world
where men and women

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:56.560
are equal whether it's
politics, whether it's sports,

00:03:56.560 --> 00:04:01.810
whether it's economy, whether
it's access to health care,

00:04:01.810 --> 00:04:05.380
in all aspects of life.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:08.510
For some people, let's say
for my four-year-old daughter,

00:04:08.510 --> 00:04:11.240
she thinks gender
equality is a given.

00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:13.706
It is something
that she completely

00:04:13.706 --> 00:04:15.330
believes that she's
in no way different

00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:18.050
from my six-year-old
son, because she's not

00:04:18.050 --> 00:04:18.920
treated differently.

00:04:18.920 --> 00:04:23.250
And she doesn't believe she has
anything up the road where she

00:04:23.250 --> 00:04:24.490
will be treated differently.

00:04:24.490 --> 00:04:28.590
She's having a ball imagining
everything is equal.

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:32.110
And as a parent, I hate
to think of that day

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:35.660
when it will suddenly click
in her head that it's not so,

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:39.170
that gender inequality is
entrenched in our society

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:41.990
no matter where
you look-- economy,

00:04:41.990 --> 00:04:45.240
politics, sports,
access to health care,

00:04:45.240 --> 00:04:47.320
the amount of leaders we have.

00:04:47.320 --> 00:04:49.040
And it's not to
say that we haven't

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:51.980
had progress there has been a
lot of progress over the years.

00:04:51.980 --> 00:04:55.830
Today there are many more women
and girls in primary education

00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:57.990
than ever before
in the world, there

00:04:57.990 --> 00:04:59.980
are many more women in
politics today than ever

00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:02.120
before in the
world, and there are

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:03.580
many more women in the economy.

00:05:03.580 --> 00:05:06.090
They're working, and
they're in paid employment.

00:05:06.090 --> 00:05:07.580
But the progress
that has happened

00:05:07.580 --> 00:05:11.840
over the last few decades
is too slow, uneven,

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:13.570
and just not enough.

00:05:13.570 --> 00:05:17.510
I say that, because
today one in three women

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:22.060
are going to be subject to
violence in their lifetimes.

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:25.430
Across the world there
are only 25 women

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:27.740
who are prime ministers
and presidents.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:31.040
In the corporate sector, since
we are in the Silicon Valley,

00:05:31.040 --> 00:05:35.090
we can't refute the fact
that there are only 25 women

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:39.630
CEOs in the Fortune
500 companies.

00:05:39.630 --> 00:05:44.610
There is a 24% wage difference
between men and women.

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:48.170
And even as we speak
right now women are dying.

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:51.050
Women are dying
every single day.

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:54.570
800 women die every
single day just trying

00:05:54.570 --> 00:06:00.110
to give life, as in childbirth,
from preventable diseases.

00:06:00.110 --> 00:06:02.390
That is unacceptable,
and that is

00:06:02.390 --> 00:06:05.480
why we say gender inequality
is still entrenched,

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:09.632
and every single day we have
to work towards changing that.

00:06:09.632 --> 00:06:11.090
FEMALE SPEAKER:
Melissa, I think it

00:06:11.090 --> 00:06:14.880
would be interesting to hear--
I think sometimes here in the US

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:17.150
we think, oh, we've
made so much progress,

00:06:17.150 --> 00:06:19.480
and these are
perhaps issues that

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:21.600
are more prevalent in
other parts of the world.

00:06:21.600 --> 00:06:25.720
Could you talk a little bit
about the US perspective,

00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:27.820
at the ACLU, some of the
things that you'll really

00:06:27.820 --> 00:06:29.080
are focused on right now?

00:06:29.080 --> 00:06:31.190
MELISSA GOODMAN: Sure
it's such a big question,

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:32.820
too, because there's
so many things.

00:06:32.820 --> 00:06:35.495
And one of the things I have
the privilege of working on

00:06:35.495 --> 00:06:38.010
at the ACLU is our
gender equity work.

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:40.710
And I guess much
like Oisika, there

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:42.950
has been tremendous
progress, but there

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:47.800
are areas where there are still
just structural differences

00:06:47.800 --> 00:06:48.470
and problems.

00:06:48.470 --> 00:06:52.200
So I'll give you my top six.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:55.200
The first I would say, and
it has a few components,

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:58.730
is really that the continuing
structural barriers,

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:01.050
stereotypes, and
unconscious bias

00:07:01.050 --> 00:07:04.270
that really still hold
women back in the workplace

00:07:04.270 --> 00:07:07.874
and translates into
less economic power.

00:07:07.874 --> 00:07:09.290
This is a global
problem, but also

00:07:09.290 --> 00:07:11.030
a problem in the United
States, and there's

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:11.946
a lot of pieces to it.

00:07:11.946 --> 00:07:16.110
We are largely far from the
time where women are officially

00:07:16.110 --> 00:07:18.545
treated differently or
shut out of jobs altogether

00:07:18.545 --> 00:07:19.420
in the United States.

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:22.640
Though I will note, the ACLU
actually does have such a case.

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:24.940
We are actually
still challenging

00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:27.640
the exclusion of women from
combat positions in the US

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:28.250
military.

00:07:28.250 --> 00:07:30.530
So it does still
happen, but largely

00:07:30.530 --> 00:07:33.900
now you what you really see is
unequal employment opportunity,

00:07:33.900 --> 00:07:37.170
and in particular
a real difference

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:39.090
between who enters
the workforce and who

00:07:39.090 --> 00:07:42.590
elevates to management
and to leadership.

00:07:42.590 --> 00:07:44.990
And it's really
about stereotypes,

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:47.840
assumption about women's
abilities and interests,

00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:51.460
what an ideal worker or
success really looks like.

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:53.470
In our mind when
we close our eyes,

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:56.800
we think of a man for
a lot of these things.

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:02.180
And it's been proven that traits
that really make men powerful,

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:04.010
and strong, and respected
in the workplace,

00:08:04.010 --> 00:08:06.830
are the very same traits
that make women less

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:12.240
likable and subject
actually to poor evaluations

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:13.160
in the workplace.

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:14.240
So there's that.

00:08:14.240 --> 00:08:18.240
There's continuing systemic
pay inequity, as Oisika noted,

00:08:18.240 --> 00:08:19.830
in the United States.

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:21.830
A big thing for us
that we're working on

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:25.680
is, and I'm only still
on the employment part,

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:27.600
is the fact that in
the United States

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:30.440
we literally have no
supports for working parents.

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:33.530
And that is not
just a female issue.

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:37.320
That is a male and female
issue, but the cultural reality

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:40.320
in our country is that
the burden of that

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:41.860
falls disproportionately
to women.

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:44.680
And we have no
paid family leave.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:47.390
In fact, only 12% of workers
in the entire country

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:49.600
have access to
paid family leave.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:52.140
I was just looking up the
statistics again today,

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:56.150
and was horrified when I read
again that 33% of new mothers

00:08:56.150 --> 00:08:59.980
takes zero time whatsoever
after their child is born.

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:04.040
And that's terrible
as a cultural reality.

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:06.050
43 million workers
in the United States

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:08.760
don't even get paid sick days
to take care of themselves

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.320
or their child when they're ill.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:12.824
And we have no system
of affordable daycare.

00:09:12.824 --> 00:09:14.990
So that's just a few of the
things in the employment

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:15.656
sector.

00:09:15.656 --> 00:09:17.530
Just a couple more things
that we work on-- I

00:09:17.530 --> 00:09:19.520
agree that the gender
gap in politics

00:09:19.520 --> 00:09:22.930
is a tremendous problem and
it exists the United States,

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:26.790
and not just other
countries that we often

00:09:26.790 --> 00:09:28.290
think we're better than.

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:29.480
Not true.

00:09:29.480 --> 00:09:31.856
There's a tremendous amount
of gender-based violence

00:09:31.856 --> 00:09:32.480
and harassment.

00:09:32.480 --> 00:09:37.700
I just heard last week that
domestic violence calls

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:41.180
are the single largest
category of calls

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:44.930
that the police in the
United States get every year.

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:47.500
Women are losing their ability
to make personal decisions

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:50.016
about whether and when to
have a child at alarming

00:09:50.016 --> 00:09:51.140
rates in the United States.

00:09:51.140 --> 00:09:54.810
Politicians remain completely
obsessed with interfering

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:57.480
with that highly personal
decision about whether to have

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:59.120
a child or have an abortion.

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:01.770
And that is something
we're seeing all the time.

00:10:01.770 --> 00:10:04.560
We're seeing girls are still
often getting education that's

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.120
full of gender stereotypes.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:09.861
And finally, I would be remiss
if I didn't also point out

00:10:09.861 --> 00:10:11.610
problems with our
criminal justice system,

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:14.040
and the gender impact that has.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:16.800
In the United States our
criminal justice system

00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:22.120
over-incarcerates women for
low-level, nonviolent, often

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:25.800
petty, poverty related offenses
at much higher rates actually

00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:26.640
than men.

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:28.900
And this just creates
a continuing cycle

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:31.900
of economic dis-empowerment,
and it separates families.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:35.320
There's 1.3 million children
living in the United States

00:10:35.320 --> 00:10:37.550
right now with
incarcerated mothers.

00:10:37.550 --> 00:10:40.899
So these are just a few of the
things we think need fixing.

