00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:11.210
HALA KAZIM: First thank
you for having me well

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:15.220
I think one of the main
thing I want to clarify

00:11:15.220 --> 00:11:21.860
is the media has given a very
negative idea to the world

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:24.410
about the Arab world.

00:11:24.410 --> 00:11:26.240
And I'm not defending
it, I'm just

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:29.420
saying that the reality
in some countries

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:34.140
are very different than
what is it really shown.

00:11:34.140 --> 00:11:36.760
The gender equality is
one of the main things

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:43.830
now UAE has-- I think six
months back [INAUDIBLE]

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:48.810
has [INAUDIBLE] has
announced a law that there

00:11:48.810 --> 00:11:52.030
is gender equality
between men and women

00:11:52.030 --> 00:11:54.530
at work in the
society and [? all. ?]

00:11:54.530 --> 00:11:58.950
And does it's really
apply in reality?

00:11:58.950 --> 00:12:00.080
Well it's around the world.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:04.830
When we really think, if I
will be very frank about it,

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:07.100
it's a man's world.

00:12:07.100 --> 00:12:12.660
And that's reality is, and
I think we women did that.

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:17.200
We have a part of that
giving them so much power.

00:12:17.200 --> 00:12:18.490
Now it's nothing wrong.

00:12:18.490 --> 00:12:20.830
We are not in a competition.

00:12:20.830 --> 00:12:23.830
I always say, it's not
like I have to be equal,

00:12:23.830 --> 00:12:24.865
like everything.

00:12:24.865 --> 00:12:28.660
There are things I know I'm
not able to do like a man,

00:12:28.660 --> 00:12:30.750
and a man cannot
do like a woman.

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:33.790
That there are a lot of things
that we can do the same.

00:12:33.790 --> 00:12:40.310
Like in our countries,
the salaries for example,

00:12:40.310 --> 00:12:41.470
we are equal.

00:12:41.470 --> 00:12:43.100
In America, it's 50%.

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:49.590
So if a man takes
$10,000.00 a month,

00:12:49.590 --> 00:12:53.750
exactly the same
$10,000.00 for a woman.

00:12:53.750 --> 00:12:57.210
It doesn't matter
the age, or whatever.

00:12:57.210 --> 00:13:03.830
It's very much equal
in that positions.

00:13:03.830 --> 00:13:07.240
Mostly I would talk about
yes, you know Arab world,

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:11.020
but you have to understand
that Arab world are not

00:13:11.020 --> 00:13:13.850
as everybody sees it
that it's one country.

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:14.930
It's so many different.

00:13:17.560 --> 00:13:23.010
The Egypt is thousands
of years of history.

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:27.440
Well, when we come to UAE, we
have done the UAE United Arab

00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:32.050
Emirates in 42 years only,
and whatever we're doing,

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:35.270
I think it's miracle.

00:13:35.270 --> 00:13:39.100
Lately [INAUDIBLE] and
they have made a law

00:13:39.100 --> 00:13:41.990
that a divorced
woman, a single woman,

00:13:41.990 --> 00:13:45.600
gets a free land like a man.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:47.690
And we do get, all
of us, I mean I'm

00:13:47.690 --> 00:13:53.400
an example of having a free
land and an interest free loan

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:55.390
for 25 years.

00:13:55.390 --> 00:13:59.530
Now this goes to all the
nationals of our country.

00:13:59.530 --> 00:14:02.190
So different countries
have different laws,

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:08.170
but I'm not saying we are
living in a la-la-land.

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:12.220
There's no perfect
country, but we are trying.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:16.190
And I think I would give
that at least to our country,

00:14:16.190 --> 00:14:18.850
that we are trying
our best, or we're

00:14:18.850 --> 00:14:26.670
doing our best to at least
take care of some shortcomings

00:14:26.670 --> 00:14:29.540
of what this reality is.

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:32.640
So I think women's
empowerment is

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:35.520
getting stronger and stronger.

00:14:35.520 --> 00:14:41.230
I think people like all of
us, there are thousands of us,

00:14:41.230 --> 00:14:43.080
that can do some changes.

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:47.290
And if I can, I'm an example
of a woman that from UAE

00:14:47.290 --> 00:14:51.330
from Dubai, and
I'm sitting here.

00:14:51.330 --> 00:14:56.290
And that shows that we
are given the chance

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:57.360
to do a lot of things.

00:14:57.360 --> 00:15:01.010
So it's, you know I don't want
to compare Arab countries,

00:15:01.010 --> 00:15:08.820
because I always say like when
an Egyptian grandmother was

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:13.460
going to the university, my
grandmother was illiterate.

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:20.830
It's so different I cannot
compare, but we're catching up,

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:24.940
and I think it's around
the world everybody's doing

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:25.874
their best.

00:15:25.874 --> 00:15:27.790
FEMALE SPEAKER: Hala,
you touched on something

00:15:27.790 --> 00:15:30.160
that I think is interesting,
and something that we've

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:33.560
seen more conversation about
this year in particular

00:15:33.560 --> 00:15:36.570
with the HeForShe campaign,
which is the role of men

00:15:36.570 --> 00:15:38.272
in this movement.

00:15:38.272 --> 00:15:39.980
You mentioned you know
women in some ways

00:15:39.980 --> 00:15:41.610
have put ourselves
in this position,

00:15:41.610 --> 00:15:43.109
or men have put us
in this position,

00:15:43.109 --> 00:15:45.600
and I think it's interesting
as we talk about empowerment.

00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:47.600
Aimee and I earlier spoke
about self-empowerment

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:51.970
versus being empowered
by some other entity.

00:15:51.970 --> 00:15:54.050
Open to anyone's
thoughts I think really,

00:15:54.050 --> 00:15:58.130
but just what is the role,
and should be the role of men

00:15:58.130 --> 00:15:59.020
in this movement?

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.460
And then I think that
the next question is--

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:03.100
what should we as
women be doing more

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:06.540
to support each other in
achieving the goals that we all

00:16:06.540 --> 00:16:08.840
have for gender equality?

00:16:08.840 --> 00:16:11.945
Anyone want to-- Arlette?

00:16:11.945 --> 00:16:18.440
ARLETTE NKURAYIJA: I will say
just to start where you are.

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:22.270
And that means everyone.

00:16:22.270 --> 00:16:26.340
It doesn't have to
be a big speech,

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:30.530
or some panel like
we doing right now.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:36.710
It helps, but I think it's
better to just keep it simple,

00:16:36.710 --> 00:16:41.770
and start where you are,
and look around you.

00:16:41.770 --> 00:16:46.330
Look at the women
around you, and it

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:50.080
could be a little conversation.

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:54.170
It could be to ask how they are.

00:16:54.170 --> 00:17:01.050
It could be to just understand
what they are going through.

00:17:01.050 --> 00:17:06.970
And in that way
small things that

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:11.637
make a difference in
every woman's life,

00:17:11.637 --> 00:17:17.879
and to be able to tell
them that they matter.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:24.690
Then you can go and
do bigger things,

00:17:24.690 --> 00:17:29.460
like education and
talking about it.

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:35.400
Then that's OK too but I think
sometimes we think that we just

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:40.960
need to do things, and we are
thinking I should do this,

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:42.470
I worked with this.

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:47.180
And it doesn't materialize,
because you are thinking

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:48.740
and you are planning.

00:17:48.740 --> 00:17:53.940
But you can just start and do
something small, but effective.

00:17:56.191 --> 00:17:57.940
OISIKA CHAKRABARTI:
Just to add onto that,

00:17:57.940 --> 00:18:00.670
and I completely resonate
with what Arlette said.

00:18:00.670 --> 00:18:02.760
So you mentioned the
HeForShe campaign.

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:05.090
So that was an initiative
that came from you

00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:07.650
and women, the campaign itself.

00:18:07.650 --> 00:18:11.190
Last year, one if our goodwill
ambassadors, Emma Watson,

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:13.070
the supremely
talented actress, she

00:18:13.070 --> 00:18:14.670
launched this HeForShe
campaign which

00:18:14.670 --> 00:18:16.450
is exactly what
Arlette was saying.

00:18:16.450 --> 00:18:19.020
It's a call to men
and boys to engage,

00:18:19.020 --> 00:18:21.300
not through an
organized movement,

00:18:21.300 --> 00:18:22.760
but in their everyday.

00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:24.900
I mean as a father, as
a brother, as a son,

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:28.890
as a supervisor at
work, at an artist

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:30.340
who is doing an exhibition.

00:18:30.340 --> 00:18:32.750
So just engage in
your everyday life,

00:18:32.750 --> 00:18:36.510
I mean to bring up your children
on a foundation of equality.

00:18:36.510 --> 00:18:38.320
That's what every father can do.

00:18:38.320 --> 00:18:42.070
To stand up for discrimination
against your colleagues

00:18:42.070 --> 00:18:43.840
when you see that
in your office.

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:48.491
So it was a way to make every
man and boy across the world

00:18:48.491 --> 00:18:49.990
sort of stand up,
and take a pledge,

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:52.160
and say OK, so I'm
going to do this.

00:18:52.160 --> 00:18:54.080
I'm going to make
sure that the women

00:18:54.080 --> 00:18:55.579
and the girls
around to me are not

00:18:55.579 --> 00:18:56.745
subjected to discrimination.

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:04.660
HALA KAZIM: I think if we
talk about how do we do it,

00:19:04.660 --> 00:19:05.810
it's from inside.

00:19:05.810 --> 00:19:08.330
You have to believe
that you can.

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:10.110
A woman should
believe in herself.

00:19:10.110 --> 00:19:12.450
And I think one of
the very main thing

00:19:12.450 --> 00:19:17.450
to help this is when
you raise your children.

00:19:17.450 --> 00:19:22.260
I have five sons, and they
have no issue with women

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:27.140
to be even better than
them, or equal to them.

00:19:27.140 --> 00:19:35.315
So I think it all starts with
us, not really from outside.

00:19:35.315 --> 00:19:36.940
AIMEE MULLINS: I
would echo that, Hala.

00:19:40.960 --> 00:19:43.670
I think for all
of us, we'd become

00:19:43.670 --> 00:19:48.080
aware of where we have
little prejudices,

00:19:48.080 --> 00:19:53.440
or we act in discriminatory
ways without even realizing it.

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:58.485
I think it's incredible to
just wake up and understand

00:19:58.485 --> 00:20:02.970
that even if you think you are
as progressive as you think

00:20:02.970 --> 00:20:06.670
you might be, there's
always a place where

00:20:06.670 --> 00:20:12.332
you're holding onto a pattern
that is probably outdated.

00:20:12.332 --> 00:20:13.840
It doesn't serve you anymore.

00:20:13.840 --> 00:20:15.990
It definitely doesn't
serve the person

00:20:15.990 --> 00:20:20.580
who is being boxed or
limited or categorized

00:20:20.580 --> 00:20:23.020
and in a limiting
way, because of that.

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:28.060
So I think the most exciting
thing about that HeForShe

00:20:28.060 --> 00:20:31.050
campaign, and similar
awareness campaigns

00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:37.796
about it, that you know
when feminism started,

00:20:37.796 --> 00:20:40.740
there was a component of
it that I think necessarily

00:20:40.740 --> 00:20:45.080
was rooted in anger at
a sense of injustice.

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:46.890
And not just a
sense of injustice,

00:20:46.890 --> 00:20:50.900
but real, experienced injustice.

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:57.510
And now that we're a
few generations on,

00:20:57.510 --> 00:20:59.990
I think the idea
that to be a feminist

00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:10.470
is to want equal treatment
of the sexes, you know,

00:21:10.470 --> 00:21:13.209
all of them.

00:21:13.209 --> 00:21:14.417
FEMALE SPEAKER: That's right.

00:21:17.370 --> 00:21:19.280
Sorry, did you want
to add something?

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:21.412
Hala you mentioned
women and violence,

00:21:21.412 --> 00:21:23.870
and I think Oisika you mentioned
some of the numbers there.

00:21:23.870 --> 00:21:28.360
And I think for people,
women especially,

00:21:28.360 --> 00:21:31.400
but people, anyone who's in
those challenging situations,

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:34.700
finding empowerment in
those really tough moments,

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:39.420
in people experiencing
daily violence or abuse--

00:21:39.420 --> 00:21:43.510
What messages, and how have you
thought about- or in your work

00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:45.350
as you are all
interacting potentially

00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:47.480
with people in those
situations- how

00:21:47.480 --> 00:21:50.420
do you think about people
there who are in that really

00:21:50.420 --> 00:21:52.270
low place of subjugation?

00:21:52.270 --> 00:21:54.390
Helping them to find
moments of empowerment,

00:21:54.390 --> 00:21:57.410
what advice would you have?

00:21:57.410 --> 00:22:01.960
ARLETTE NKURAYIJA:
It is to go back

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:05.180
to every single person
as an individual.

00:22:08.800 --> 00:22:13.670
Everyone is unique,
and it will be

00:22:13.670 --> 00:22:20.300
pretentious to think that
because you have an experience.

00:22:20.300 --> 00:22:23.140
Or you have been
through so much,

00:22:23.140 --> 00:22:28.010
that it's going to
help someone else.

00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:30.100
It could, but it's not.

00:22:30.100 --> 00:22:35.690
So it has to be always
about the other person.

00:22:35.690 --> 00:22:38.880
And it has always to
be also about you,

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:43.490
because-- I will
give an example.

00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:50.080
I am a survivor of
genocide, and I really

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:54.150
don't like to say
that about myself,

00:22:54.150 --> 00:22:57.590
because that's how people
sees me: as a survivor.

00:22:57.590 --> 00:23:02.300
That I feel like
I am human being.

00:23:02.300 --> 00:23:04.490
What happened was hard.

00:23:04.490 --> 00:23:11.220
It was a situation that I didn't
cause, but that helps me now.

00:23:11.220 --> 00:23:14.230
When it was happening,
I couldn't get it.

00:23:14.230 --> 00:23:18.020
And if someone
would have come then

00:23:18.020 --> 00:23:23.590
and told me because they
went through something,

00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:28.340
it will help me, I will
have not resonated then.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:35.950
So I feel like every time
someone needs, whatever

00:23:35.950 --> 00:23:38.930
they need, help, inspiration.

00:23:38.930 --> 00:23:45.330
You can always go from where you
are and tell them your story,

00:23:45.330 --> 00:23:50.010
and tell it in a way
that is true to you,

00:23:50.010 --> 00:23:54.760
and sometimes going to resonate
with them, sometimes not.

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:57.890
But you have to understand
that it's not about you,

00:23:57.890 --> 00:23:59.220
it's about them.

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:04.010
And if you are able
to help someone

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:13.530
you really have to remember
that the uniqueness has to come

00:24:13.530 --> 00:24:15.870
from them back from you.

00:24:15.870 --> 00:24:19.500
But sometimes you need
also to be practical

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:26.110
because there is some situation
when needs active action.

00:24:26.110 --> 00:24:33.940
And I'm thinking of
a woman in my work

00:24:33.940 --> 00:24:37.580
that I come across
that are very sick.

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:44.500
And you need to treat the
physical disease first

00:24:44.500 --> 00:24:46.950
to be able to have
that conversation.

00:24:46.950 --> 00:24:52.600
So I think as I said
before, to start where

00:24:52.600 --> 00:24:54.950
you are is the most
important thing,

00:24:54.950 --> 00:24:57.130
and to see what's going on.

00:24:57.130 --> 00:25:02.430
Not to feel like
you have, of course

00:25:02.430 --> 00:25:09.065
you have to make a difference,
but in someone others life.

00:25:12.941 --> 00:25:14.316
MELISSA GOODMAN:
I was just going

00:25:14.316 --> 00:25:18.400
to add though, that was
very powerful, Arlette.

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:21.990
I think the thing that I
like to try to remind people

00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:23.980
in that situation,
is that no matter

00:25:23.980 --> 00:25:28.490
how powerless they feel
in a particular situation

00:25:28.490 --> 00:25:31.990
or in that particular moment,
to know that they still

00:25:31.990 --> 00:25:33.350
have power.

00:25:33.350 --> 00:25:36.090
And they still have
ownership over themselves.

00:25:36.090 --> 00:25:40.830
And that they very simply
they are not alone.

00:25:40.830 --> 00:25:43.040
Often it can help
to talk to others,

00:25:43.040 --> 00:25:45.540
but unfortunately
we live in a world

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:51.880
where over a million women are
sexually assaulted every year.

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:56.350
Myself, also, as survivor of
some form of sexual violence.

00:25:56.350 --> 00:26:00.590
I think that it's important
to say that, to own that,

00:26:00.590 --> 00:26:04.880
and to tell people
that it's very hard,

00:26:04.880 --> 00:26:06.470
but there is another side.

00:26:06.470 --> 00:26:08.270
You get through
to the other side,

00:26:08.270 --> 00:26:10.990
and there could be an
enormous amount of power

00:26:10.990 --> 00:26:15.090
on the other side, and
that you're not alone

00:26:15.090 --> 00:26:18.800
HALA KAZIM: I think
to me, what I really

00:26:18.800 --> 00:26:24.030
would always say to any woman,
to learn to love herself.

00:26:24.030 --> 00:26:26.180
And I think that's
where we don't know.

00:26:26.180 --> 00:26:32.290
I think we abuse
ourselves, and we

00:26:32.290 --> 00:26:34.660
don't take care of
ourselves, because we're

00:26:34.660 --> 00:26:38.800
programmed that we should
always do something for someone.

00:26:38.800 --> 00:26:42.030
And I think if you really
learn to love yourself--

00:26:42.030 --> 00:26:46.170
like loving yourself, it
doesn't mean you're selfish.

00:26:46.170 --> 00:26:48.660
It means you can
give people more,

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:51.030
because you take
care of yourself.

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:58.305
And when I meet people with
problems, they get puzzled.

00:26:58.305 --> 00:26:59.800
What do you mean
I love yourself?

00:26:59.800 --> 00:27:01.515
Of course I love myself.

00:27:01.515 --> 00:27:03.820
And I'm like, "OK let's talk."

00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:08.870
Then in the end she says,
"I know now, I don't."

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:11.910
And I say, "Loving
is not a handbag.

00:27:11.910 --> 00:27:14.210
It's not a trip.

00:27:14.210 --> 00:27:17.130
It's how you take care
of your well-being."

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:21.780
And that's all my company,
or my program I would say,

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:26.680
is all about: taking
care of yourself

00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:29.240
in this journey of life.

00:27:29.240 --> 00:27:32.540
And when you know how to
take care of your well-being

00:27:32.540 --> 00:27:38.000
emotionally, physically,
this is spiritually,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:40.980
and intellectually, everything.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:42.800
And I'm not saying
going to be perfect.

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:43.880
None of us are perfect.

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:46.380
There are no perfection;
we would not be human.

00:27:46.380 --> 00:27:49.630
But at least you
have the stability

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:53.230
of living a good life.

00:27:53.230 --> 00:27:57.650
Then you really can put this
person with anyone, anywhere,

00:27:57.650 --> 00:28:01.200
and they can do good, because
they're good to themselves.

00:28:04.994 --> 00:28:06.680
AIMEE MULLINS: I think
this programming,

00:28:06.680 --> 00:28:10.330
we've all touched on this,
starts very, very young.

00:28:10.330 --> 00:28:12.460
I know that I've
become very aware

00:28:12.460 --> 00:28:14.970
now that my friends
and peer group

00:28:14.970 --> 00:28:17.780
are starting to become parents.

00:28:17.780 --> 00:28:24.570
That I don't say to a little
girl "Oh, you're so beautiful!"

00:28:24.570 --> 00:28:28.110
That will not be the
first thing I say to her.

00:28:28.110 --> 00:28:31.670
It's a little rule
for myself, because I

00:28:31.670 --> 00:28:36.300
find it interesting to hear the
things that were said to me,

00:28:36.300 --> 00:28:41.776
or I would easily say
if I was babysitting.

00:28:41.776 --> 00:28:43.630
You say things to
girls that you don't

00:28:43.630 --> 00:28:47.560
say to boys in the sense
of be sweet, smile.

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:50.810
These things start from
a very young age where

00:28:50.810 --> 00:28:52.870
it's about being palatable.

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:55.510
And I know from my
experience as an athlete.

00:28:55.510 --> 00:29:00.400
Every year, a number of the
greatest female athletes

00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:04.330
in the world gather in New York
City for the women's sports

00:29:04.330 --> 00:29:06.440
foundation, which
Billie Jean King, who's

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:11.280
a wonderful advocate in many
areas, founded in the '70s.

00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:14.470
And the athletes
do their own dinner

00:29:14.470 --> 00:29:16.930
the night before, like at a
bowling alley kind of thing.

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:20.239
Really not competitive, right?

00:29:20.239 --> 00:29:22.405
But we get together and we
go around the room first,

00:29:22.405 --> 00:29:25.909
and it's sort of the
opportunity for the rookies,

00:29:25.909 --> 00:29:27.450
the people never
been to that dinner,

00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:29.110
to introduce themselves.

00:29:29.110 --> 00:29:33.370
And it's extraordinary
how people, we're

00:29:33.370 --> 00:29:37.820
talking about Olympic and
world record setting athletes

00:29:37.820 --> 00:29:40.400
or professional
athletes, and how we've

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:44.500
been taught to dumb it down.

00:29:44.500 --> 00:29:46.050
To not be threatening.

00:29:46.050 --> 00:29:49.440
So it has become a little
ritual at this dinner

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:51.620
to be ridiculous.

00:29:51.620 --> 00:29:53.570
Because it would start
by saying, "Yeah,

00:29:53.570 --> 00:29:55.432
I play softball."

00:29:55.432 --> 00:29:58.040
Oh OK, that's what
the rookie says,

00:29:58.040 --> 00:29:59.790
and the next person
says, "Well, you know,

00:29:59.790 --> 00:30:01.590
I set three world records."

00:30:01.590 --> 00:30:03.890
And then the rookie goes,
"Well, I actually I am,

00:30:03.890 --> 00:30:05.910
I do have the record
for the most--".

00:30:05.910 --> 00:30:09.600
It's become, like in
this safe environment,

00:30:09.600 --> 00:30:15.960
can you be wildly
celebratory of yourself,

00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:20.180
and not have it equate to a
derogatory feeling of shame

00:30:20.180 --> 00:30:22.035
or you're not being humble?

00:30:25.590 --> 00:30:28.530
And it is sometimes these
little steps of that.

00:30:28.530 --> 00:30:31.900
It just happened for me in
the bathroom here at Google.

00:30:31.900 --> 00:30:34.519
A woman said to
me that she was--

00:30:34.519 --> 00:30:36.060
we were talking
about sports, and she

00:30:36.060 --> 00:30:39.250
said this she was doing
Olympic weightlifting.

00:30:39.250 --> 00:30:41.800
And then she spent the next
five minutes telling me, "Well,

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:42.930
but for fun.

00:30:42.930 --> 00:30:44.600
Well, more for fun,
not just for fun,

00:30:44.600 --> 00:30:45.815
because you have to
work at it, but you

00:30:45.815 --> 00:30:47.314
know I don't really
do it the way--"

00:30:47.314 --> 00:30:49.985
And I listened to her
and I said at the end,

00:30:49.985 --> 00:30:51.360
"You know, if you
were a guy, you

00:30:51.360 --> 00:30:52.651
wouldn't have said any of that.

00:30:52.651 --> 00:30:55.144
You would've just said, yeah,
I do Olympic weightlifting."

00:30:55.144 --> 00:30:56.810
FEMALE SPEAKER: And
be very proud of it.

00:30:56.810 --> 00:30:58.018
AIMEE MULLINS: And that's it.

00:30:58.018 --> 00:31:03.190
Own it, and not have to
couch it so that you could

00:31:03.190 --> 00:31:05.410
make it more palatable for me.

00:31:05.410 --> 00:31:07.580
I think it's amazing.

00:31:07.580 --> 00:31:11.580
But it's something I've become
aware of, because I do it too,

00:31:11.580 --> 00:31:13.040
and we all do it.

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:19.670
And I just think that
becoming aware of, and having

00:31:19.670 --> 00:31:23.480
little reminders to ourselves
and to our friends, I think

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:27.410
is just how we do start
to make that change.

00:31:27.410 --> 00:31:30.370
HALA KAZIM: I think we're
brought up in the Cinderella

00:31:30.370 --> 00:31:37.610
syndrome, that we have to
always wait for someone,

00:31:37.610 --> 00:31:39.820
or we won't be complete.

00:31:39.820 --> 00:31:45.420
Are programmed in a way
that you don't ask for much,

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:46.970
because you're not supposed to.

00:31:46.970 --> 00:31:50.010
You should, you know,
in different culture

00:31:50.010 --> 00:31:56.200
a woman should not raise
her voice or laugh loud,

00:31:56.200 --> 00:32:00.164
because it's not proper.

00:32:00.164 --> 00:32:02.580
FEMALE SPEAKER: I want to touch
on just one of the themes,

00:32:02.580 --> 00:32:04.038
and this is really
interesting kind

00:32:04.038 --> 00:32:05.550
of interplay the
conversation we're

00:32:05.550 --> 00:32:08.800
having between really personal
choices that people make,

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:11.880
and then the structure in which
those choices kind of manifest.

00:32:11.880 --> 00:32:16.000
And the interplay that I
think we're in a lot as women,

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:17.520
you feel empowered
one day and then

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:21.130
maybe you bump up against a
decision being made about pay

00:32:21.130 --> 00:32:24.181
scale, or a decision
about leadership that

00:32:24.181 --> 00:32:26.680
doesn't go your way, and all
of a sudden that's a step back.

00:32:26.680 --> 00:32:29.110
That's a setback.

00:32:29.110 --> 00:32:32.154
It does seem like a couple of
you touched on the leadership

00:32:32.154 --> 00:32:33.820
imbalance, that there's
some things that

00:32:33.820 --> 00:32:36.450
could be done by getting more
women into those leadership

00:32:36.450 --> 00:32:41.070
decision making positions,
such that those norms

00:32:41.070 --> 00:32:44.040
and cultures can start to
shift from a much higher level.

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:47.210
How do you think about the
right ways of going about that?

00:32:47.210 --> 00:32:49.650
I know, Melissa, you're
working hard on this

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:52.275
in the film industry right now
with directors and producers.

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:58.410
I know Aimee is also working in
a different vein in that way.

00:32:58.410 --> 00:33:00.790
So obviously that's one
particular industry,

00:33:00.790 --> 00:33:02.219
but we see this
across government

00:33:02.219 --> 00:33:03.260
across corporate America.

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:05.490
All the stats that
Oisika started this with.

00:33:05.490 --> 00:33:07.547
How does that play
into this conversation?

00:33:07.547 --> 00:33:09.130
MELISSA GOODMAN:
Sure, well I'll start

00:33:09.130 --> 00:33:13.280
and try to be very brief about
it, because your question also

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:15.180
I think relates to
the last question,

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:16.870
and what we were all
saying about what

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:17.890
we're taught so early.

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:20.190
So I have been recently,
relatively obsessed

00:33:20.190 --> 00:33:23.350
about gender bias in
Hollywood, in particular

00:33:23.350 --> 00:33:25.539
looking at women directors.

00:33:25.539 --> 00:33:27.330
And a lot of people
sort of asked me, like,

00:33:27.330 --> 00:33:29.380
why is this something the
ACLU is paying attention to?

00:33:29.380 --> 00:33:31.120
Why is this a civil
liberties problem?

00:33:31.120 --> 00:33:33.020
And I think this
conversation is actually

00:33:33.020 --> 00:33:34.650
the explanation of why.

00:33:34.650 --> 00:33:40.390
One, it's a huge leadership
position in Hollywood.

00:33:40.390 --> 00:33:45.260
But most importantly,
TV and film

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:49.560
are two of our most
important cultural products.

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:53.120
And the fact that literally
women are essentially

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:57.840
excluded from directing big
budget studio feature films,

00:33:57.840 --> 00:34:00.480
and are seriously
under-represented in directing

00:34:00.480 --> 00:34:03.480
television, it's not just
a civil rights problem.

00:34:03.480 --> 00:34:05.870
Because you know,
note to Hollywood,

00:34:05.870 --> 00:34:07.860
you do have to comply
with civil rights laws.

00:34:07.860 --> 00:34:10.820
You are not exempt, even though
the culture is otherwise.

00:34:10.820 --> 00:34:15.750
What we see on those screens has
a tremendous cultural impact.

00:34:15.750 --> 00:34:18.230
And that's one of
the reasons we're

00:34:18.230 --> 00:34:20.130
devoting so much time
and energy to this,

00:34:20.130 --> 00:34:23.420
because our biggest cultural
product is overwhelmingly

00:34:23.420 --> 00:34:25.210
being made by men.

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:29.960
The stories are male stories,
told from a male eye.

00:34:29.960 --> 00:34:31.649
Women are depicted
through a male eye.

00:34:31.649 --> 00:34:33.190
And I'm not saying,
you know, there's

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:36.289
not-- there's plenty of feminist
film and TV makers out there.

00:34:36.289 --> 00:34:37.830
But studies have
shown, when you have

00:34:37.830 --> 00:34:39.909
more women behind
the camera, not

00:34:39.909 --> 00:34:42.480
only are more women depicted,
but the way in which they're

00:34:42.480 --> 00:34:47.370
depicted, and the reduction in
stereotypes, the more speaking

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:49.250
lines literally that women have.

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:50.630
It's tremendously important.

00:34:50.630 --> 00:34:52.880
So a lot of people think
like, why are you doing that?

00:34:52.880 --> 00:34:54.389
That's one of the reasons.

00:34:54.389 --> 00:34:57.580
So we look at industries where
women really are effectively

00:34:57.580 --> 00:34:59.330
shut out from leadership.

00:34:59.330 --> 00:35:02.200
And I guess the last thing
I'd say about that, only

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:07.720
because I'd be remiss, because
I'm sitting in Google, most

00:35:07.720 --> 00:35:11.010
of our very powerful industries
here in the United States

00:35:11.010 --> 00:35:13.000
do have tremendous
gender bias problems.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:16.729
And tech is, as I'm sure many of
you know, you know one of them.

00:35:16.729 --> 00:35:18.645
And when you were saying
leadership positions,

00:35:18.645 --> 00:35:20.990
you know unfortunately, that
this stat I read recently

00:35:20.990 --> 00:35:23.550
is only 9% of senior
management positions

00:35:23.550 --> 00:35:26.050
in Silicon Valley
are held by women.

00:35:26.050 --> 00:35:28.660
And we have to start
examining the disconnect

00:35:28.660 --> 00:35:31.700
between the equality that we
have at the educational stage.

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:35.330
Women are generally in college
and even in graduate school,

00:35:35.330 --> 00:35:37.089
you know, graduating
at equal rates.

00:35:37.089 --> 00:35:39.380
But somehow when you look at
those leadership positions

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:41.230
the numbers drop
dramatically and we

00:35:41.230 --> 00:35:43.069
need to start working on that.

00:35:43.069 --> 00:35:44.610
OISIKA CHAKRABARTI:
Yeah, absolutely.

00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:47.700
And UN Women also works
on this area of media,

00:35:47.700 --> 00:35:49.790
because there's
this huge challenge

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:51.734
as Melissa was saying.

00:35:51.734 --> 00:35:53.650
And we work in the news
rooms trying to expand

00:35:53.650 --> 00:35:55.150
the dialogue on media.

00:35:55.150 --> 00:35:56.990
But speaking about
leadership as a whole,

00:35:56.990 --> 00:35:59.590
I think the challenge
is here in the US.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:01.430
But it's also a challenge
across the world

00:36:01.430 --> 00:36:04.990
where what's considered the
cohort of how many people

00:36:04.990 --> 00:36:08.340
you need in Parliament to make
a move towards a different law

00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:09.550
is 30%.

00:36:09.550 --> 00:36:12.630
And most countries haven't
got anywhere close.

00:36:12.630 --> 00:36:17.090
United States is 75th on that
scale, and it has about 20%,

00:36:17.090 --> 00:36:20.492
whereas Rwanda has 67%.

00:36:20.492 --> 00:36:22.200
So Rwanda is one of
those countries which

00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:25.630
came after the reconstruction
where women became leaders,

00:36:25.630 --> 00:36:28.560
because the men were
not there in government,

00:36:28.560 --> 00:36:29.952
and politics, and everything.

00:36:29.952 --> 00:36:31.660
But I also want to
come back a little bit

00:36:31.660 --> 00:36:34.580
to the last question about
choice and self identification

00:36:34.580 --> 00:36:35.600
and empowerment.

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:38.490
But what do you do when there
are no services to turn to?

00:36:38.490 --> 00:36:42.232
Across the world, I might be
a domestic violence survivor.

00:36:42.232 --> 00:36:43.940
I might think this is
dangerous, and it's

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:46.660
dangerous for me and my
children to stay in this house,

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:50.110
but where do I go?

00:36:50.110 --> 00:36:52.829
And I think that also comes
from what Aimee was saying

00:36:52.829 --> 00:36:54.120
earlier, how you're brought up.

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:57.560
For a person like me, I
would know that I have a job,

00:36:57.560 --> 00:37:00.430
or I would know that I have
a father's household where

00:37:00.430 --> 00:37:02.020
they would say just come back.

00:37:02.020 --> 00:37:02.730
He's abusive?

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:04.020
Come back, it's fine.

00:37:04.020 --> 00:37:06.539
But most people don't have
that luxury of choice.

00:37:06.539 --> 00:37:07.330
So what do they do?

00:37:07.330 --> 00:37:09.690
They look for an NGO
or a shelter to go to,

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:10.990
and there are none.

00:37:10.990 --> 00:37:13.080
So when there are
more women leaders,

00:37:13.080 --> 00:37:15.090
they also look for
these kind of services.

00:37:15.090 --> 00:37:17.960
They try to move policy
towards having more shelters,

00:37:17.960 --> 00:37:21.140
of having a place where domestic
violence survivors can go.

00:37:21.140 --> 00:37:22.950
So in India where
I'm from, there

00:37:22.950 --> 00:37:25.660
is a whole democracy movement
happening at the grassroots

00:37:25.660 --> 00:37:26.240
level.

00:37:26.240 --> 00:37:27.420
And the national parliament?

00:37:27.420 --> 00:37:29.850
No, there are not many
women in politics,

00:37:29.850 --> 00:37:32.140
and we are a very
long way to go to get

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:34.160
to the 30% I was talking about.

00:37:34.160 --> 00:37:39.157
And the 30% is a benchmark that
was talked about 20 years back

00:37:39.157 --> 00:37:40.240
at the Beijing conference.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:43.660
So that's what I was saying,
the progress is too slow.

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:46.180
But at the grassroots level,
at the [INAUDIBLE] level.

00:37:46.180 --> 00:37:48.720
What we called the
Village Council.

00:37:48.720 --> 00:37:54.040
There is about a billion--
there is a huge movement where

00:37:54.040 --> 00:37:55.861
women are becoming leaders.

00:37:55.861 --> 00:37:57.110
And what are they looking for?

00:37:57.110 --> 00:37:59.270
They looking for
the water should

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:00.950
be close to the
household, so that women

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:03.741
don't have to walk for
hours trying to get water.

00:38:03.741 --> 00:38:05.990
They're looking for a primary
school in their village,

00:38:05.990 --> 00:38:07.720
so that little girls
and little boys

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:09.760
can go to school in
a sustained basis.

00:38:09.760 --> 00:38:12.270
Not just go one day and
then drop out the next day.

00:38:12.270 --> 00:38:14.270
So when women
become leaders they

00:38:14.270 --> 00:38:17.310
are also looking for
societal change, and not

00:38:17.310 --> 00:38:19.110
just cosmetic changes
many of the time.

00:38:19.110 --> 00:38:21.710
So we do need more
women in leadership

00:38:21.710 --> 00:38:24.260
here in the STEM industry,
in politics, in government,

00:38:24.260 --> 00:38:24.760
everywhere.

00:38:28.546 --> 00:38:30.670
FEMALE SPEAKER: So I think
we are close to the time

00:38:30.670 --> 00:38:32.128
that we should be
wrapping this up,

00:38:32.128 --> 00:38:34.560
but we could obviously
keep this conversation

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:36.470
going for many hours.

00:38:36.470 --> 00:38:39.550
I think it would be great to get
some final thoughts from some

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:42.890
of you on what change
you think is actually

00:38:42.890 --> 00:38:45.387
possible in our
lifetime on this issue.

00:38:45.387 --> 00:38:47.720
I think you've talked a little
bit about progress that's

00:38:47.720 --> 00:38:50.120
been made, and sitting
here in Silicon Valley

00:38:50.120 --> 00:38:52.800
we're always at the
nexus of the future.

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:57.520
And thinking about what with
all of the energy that we have,

00:38:57.520 --> 00:39:01.290
and all of the leadership
roles that people have taken,

00:39:01.290 --> 00:39:02.790
what change do we
really think could

00:39:02.790 --> 00:39:03.998
be possible in this lifetime?

00:39:06.640 --> 00:39:08.890
MELISSA GOODMAN: I feel like
everyone turned this way.

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:11.880
Oh my goodness,
so much pressure!

00:39:11.880 --> 00:39:13.700
I feel like I'm
talking too much.

00:39:13.700 --> 00:39:17.912
I'll just say I always sound
like a cynic on these panels,

00:39:17.912 --> 00:39:19.370
but I'm actually
truly an idealist.

00:39:19.370 --> 00:39:21.869
I wouldn't be able to kind of
wake up and do what I do every

00:39:21.869 --> 00:39:23.080
day if I wasn't.

00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:24.872
I really think, and
this is not necessarily

00:39:24.872 --> 00:39:26.329
just through suing
people, it's not

00:39:26.329 --> 00:39:27.540
the only thing the ACLU does.

00:39:27.540 --> 00:39:30.320
But I feel confident
that, and I'll only

00:39:30.320 --> 00:39:32.720
speak from a US
perspective at the moment

00:39:32.720 --> 00:39:35.420
because I don't feel
qualified to speak otherwise.

00:39:35.420 --> 00:39:38.869
I feel like we can
get-- I don't remember

00:39:38.869 --> 00:39:39.910
the time period you said.

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:42.040
But I think some
of the changes we

00:39:42.040 --> 00:39:45.730
need to make in the
workplace are attainable.

00:39:45.730 --> 00:39:48.560
We're not, in a
cultural way, going

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:54.320
to erase eons of the way
we view gender roles.

00:39:54.320 --> 00:39:58.130
We're not going to eliminate
unconscious bias tomorrow.

00:39:58.130 --> 00:39:59.900
But I think we can
make practical changes

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:04.040
in the workplace that neutralize
people's unconscious bias

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:05.770
in the way that
we conduct hiring.

00:40:05.770 --> 00:40:09.390
In the way that we evaluate
candidates for jobs.

00:40:09.390 --> 00:40:12.720
In the way that we structure
our workplaces to be,

00:40:12.720 --> 00:40:15.480
not only more supportive of
working families, but moving

00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:19.240
towards a culture,
as Google does

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:23.380
espouse of kind of treating
workers as whole people.

00:40:23.380 --> 00:40:26.150
That is something that is like
a radical, important gender

00:40:26.150 --> 00:40:28.760
equality idea as well,
and very important.

00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:33.310
And I think if we seriously
devoted time to doing that,

00:40:33.310 --> 00:40:38.780
and thought about things like
family needs, and pay equity,

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:42.105
and the needs that workers
have outside of work,

00:40:42.105 --> 00:40:43.480
I think we could
come a long way.

00:40:46.480 --> 00:40:49.160
ARLETTE NKURAYIJA:
To me, I think

00:40:49.160 --> 00:40:54.850
removing limitations one by
one, because there's so many.

00:40:54.850 --> 00:41:01.860
And it's a matter of just
taking one at a time.

00:41:06.490 --> 00:41:10.940
When you asked me
the question before,

00:41:10.940 --> 00:41:14.750
it was after everyone
spoke, thinking

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:22.150
about the labeling of people,
and how you see someone

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:27.900
and you just want to
define that person.

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:34.580
And I was thinking
when also Aimee

00:41:34.580 --> 00:41:37.610
was speaking about
when you see a girl,

